name: Mariposa
lyrics:
[Chorus: Joseph]
I can't wait for you to come my way
I've been far away
But I'll keep running
Just to find a way to you till then

[Verse 1: Tarrek]
I've been running from it
Tired of running from it
Scared of feeling something
Now I'm stuck here tryna get up outta this hole
I tried to be strong
I tried to make it work but I've been feeling too numb
Skies are beating on me
Why'd you leave me lonely?
Feeling Whitney, Stoney
Now I'm stuck here wondering where I ever went wrong
How could I be strong?
I'm fighting for your love

[Chorus: Joseph]
I can't wait for you to come my way
I've been far away
But I'll keep running
Just to find a way to you till then
[Verse 2: Issac]
I don't see light in your love anymore
There ain't no reason to call in a fall
I don't like feelings and feeling like running from something
And feeling so out of control
I know that the feelings are gone
I'm spending too much time alone
I'm hoping you pick up the phone
And ring me when you wanna stay overnight
My shoulder's right
My baby's all that I want
And I play them, all of my favourite songs
That lady is my favourite one

[Chorus: Joseph]
I can't wait for you to come my way
I've been far away
But I'll keep running
Just to find a way to you till then

[Bridge: Joseph]
Ain't never gonna let you go
Got my heart NASCAR racing
Shine ain't never fading
He just left you hanging
Fiending for your love
All worth it for the waiting
Give you what you need
Take you where you want
Can't feel it when we're all alone
Know you're wanting something more
My heart is like an open door
Just ring me when you wanna go
[Break: Joseph]
I'll wait till you're home
Hold a place till you're coming home
Show you where the garden grows
Just ring me when you wanna go

[Chorus: Joseph]
I can't wait for you to come my way
I've been far away
But I'll keep running
Just to find a way to you till then
annotations:
[('My heart is like an open door', [['“My heart is like an open door” is a reference to the Famous Frozen soundtrack “Love is an open door” meaning his heart is open and is ready to accept her back or ready to love her. Or, It has nothing to do with that song and it just means his heart is open.']]), ('I don’t see light in your love anymore
 There ain’t no reason to call in a fall
 I don’t like feelings and feeling like running from something
 And feeling so out of control
 I know that the feelings are gone
 I’m spending too much time alone', [['The speaker knows that their SO does not love them the same way anymore. They can tell that their SO has given up on the relationship which is why there is no “light” in the artificial love that they show to the speaker. The speaker is fully aware of this but wants to avoid confrontation, even though they dislike feeling like they’re running away from their problems.']]), ('Hold a place till you’re coming home', [['Again, the singer is placing no pressure on the person to make a decision. Its making the person aware that there is a place in him always.']]), ('He just left you hanging
 Fiending for your love
 All worth it for the waiting
 Give you what you need
 Take you where you want
 Can’t feel it when we’re all alone', [['The person referred to in this song has tried to start something with another person, however they were left hanging. This part of the song reminds the lover that they will be there waiting for them to realise that they are the right one for them. The song is stepping back and letting the person realise this for themselves']]), ('But I’ll keep running', [['If you are a big fan of the Peach Tree Rascals, you’ll notice that a common ‘activity’ in their music videos includes shots of the members running. Just running with no set destination.

This line, in combination of the prior lyrics combines to show that the singer is not running to a set person or away from anyone. But is just running, if they cross paths with the desired person-then so be it.']]), ('Feeling Whitney, Stoney', [['“Feeling Whitney, Stoney” is a reference to “Feeling Whitney” by Post Malone. The song is generally regarded as sad.']])]

name: Put Your Records On
lyrics:
[Verse 1]
Three little birds sat on my window
And they told me I don't need to worry
Summer came like cinnamon, so sweet
Little girls double-dutch on the concrete

[Pre-Chorus 1]
Maybe sometimes we got it wrong, but it's all right
The more things seem to change, the more they stay the same
Don't you hesitate

[Chorus]
Girl, put your records on, tell me your favorite song
You go ahead, let your hair down
Sapphire and faded jeans, I hope you get your dreams
Just go ahead, let your hair down

[Post-Chorus]
You're gonna find yourself somewhere, somehow

[Verse 2]
Blue as the sky, sunburnt and lonely
Sipping tea in the bar by the roadside (Just relax, just relax)
Don't you let those other boys fool you
Gotta love that afro hairdo
[Pre-Chorus 2]
Maybe sometimes we feel afraid, but it's all right
The more you stay the same, the more that they seem to change
Don't ya think it's strange?

[Chorus]
Girl, put your records on, tell me your favorite song
You go ahead, let your hair down
Sapphire and faded jeans, I hope you get your dreams
Just go ahead, let your hair down

[Post-Chorus]
You're gonna find yourself somewhere, somehow

[Bridge]
Just more than I could take, pity for pity's sake
Some nights kept me awake, I thought that I was stronger
When you gonna realize that you don't even have to try any longer?
Do what you want to

[Outro]
Girl, put your records on, tell me your favorite song
Just go ahead, let your hair down
Sapphire and faded jeans, I hope you get your dreams
Just go ahead, let your hair down
You're gonna find yourself somewhere, somehow
annotations:
[('Girl, put your records on,', [['I found that as a young person, music was a really amazing way to find confidence and to find self expression. You could always find that song that’s like, “That’s just me. That person knows exactly how I feel.” Certain pop songs. I feel like I just put on music and feel like invincible and super confident and bold and let the music sort of carry you. To me, that’s what my favorite song is doing. It would turn me from being someone that was shy or self conscious or uncomfortable into a feeling really sort of bold and confident while that song is on, you kind of live in the song.

-Corinne Bailey Rae (original artist)']]), ('Tell me your favorite song', [['When I was a kid, I loved this Mariah Carey song called “Vision of Love.” And I used to sort of sing that in the mirror with the hairbrush and just be like, “She’s amazing.” My dad had just gotten a CD player so it’s like early ‘90s and I had to put it on repeat and that’s me for like an hour, just listening to that one song.

-Corinne Bailey Rae (original artist)']]), ('You go ahead, let your hair down', [['I’ve had a few experiences of wearing my hair out and natural for the first time. I used to just tie it back and have it permed and then I’ve had relaxed super straight, probably short and straight hair.

I remember when I first started wearing it out and feeling self conscious and people were making fun of me as well because it’s so different, and living in England, it was against what was considered to be a nice way to have your hair.


-Corinne Bailey Rae (original artist)']]), ('Just go ahead, let your hair down', [['I’ve had a few experiences of wearing my hair out and natural for the first time. I used to just tie it back and have it permed and then I’ve had relaxed super straight, probably short and straight hair.

I remember when I first started wearing it out and feeling self conscious and people were making fun of me as well because it’s so different, and living in England, it was against what was considered to be a nice way to have your hair.


-Corinne Bailey Rae (original artist)']]), ('Little girls double-dutch on the concrete', [['Double Dutch is a game in which two long jump ropes turning in opposite directions are jumped by one or more players jumping simultaneously.']]), ('And they told me I don’t need to worry', [['In Bob Marley’s “Three Little Birds”, he sings “Don’t worry about a thing.”']]), ('Three little birds sat on my window', [['This is a reference to Bob Marley & The Wailers‘ “Three Little Birds” from the group’s ninth studio album Exodus.']])]

annotations:
[('Stone cold, will you miss me?', [['“Stone“ is a (historically) lesbian identity (and now expanded to other identities) that refers to a sexual partner who prefers to give sexual pleasure physically but not receive it. The classic book Stone Butch Blues by Leslie Feinberg explores this identity and is well known within the queer community. There are nuances to this dynamic but based on the exploration of 1950s butch/femme dynamics in this song it seems like this is a pretty overt callout to a stone butch.']]), ('I hope that you’re happy with me in your life
 I hope that you won’t slip away in the night
 I hope that you’re happy with me in your life
 I hope that you won’t slip away
 I hate it when dudes try to chase me
 I love it when you try to save me
 ‘Cause I’m just a lady', [['I wrote the verse one coming out of the shower and I wrote the chorus melody by myself. Then I went into the studio, I called my engineer Mike Malgerhoff, and I was like, “We got to get in this weekend.” Basically the next day, the next two days, I went to the studio and was like, “Nick you got to come in here help me finish this shit.”

Nick came in and it was me, Nick and Mike, and we’re sitting there and I played him the verse and the chorus. He’s like, “Dude Fuck yeah.” Then  we were like the melodies are done, let’s just get the second verse and let’s get the chorus lyrics in. It really started verse one, chorus, and then we wrote verse two and the bridge obviously. It changed very little from the demo also. The song was recorded almost two years ago, and it really has stayed almost the same. Which makes me super happy because it’s my production. I worked with my two very good friends on it.

“I hope that you’re happy with me in your life
I hope that you won’t slip away"—that’s sad. That’s a sad lyric. The song is about love and fear and the way you present yourself in relationships. There’s a lot of uncertainty in the lyrics. "Did you mean it when you said I was pretty?” And talking about someone not kissing you until you least expect it, it’s these moments of uncertainty that we all feel when we’re in love. I think that that lyric is just the summation of all of those feelings. “Are you gonna fucking leave me? Just want a heads up would be great ya know.”

I love that its so matter of fact. When I listen back to it the bridge, it’s always like “Awe.” It’s like a moment of sad reflection.']]), ('That you didn’t wanna live in a city
 Where the people are shitty?', [['When I was writing that, I was writing it from the perspective of somebody who moved from New York to LA. The whole EP is about this transition from New York to LA in a way. I think when I left New York I was really angry at New York just because I was. I felt like I was rejecting it in order to not miss it. I just love that, “I don’t wanna live in a city where the people are shitty.” I felt that way about New York for a moment and now I’m nostalgic for it. I’m happy I’m back obviously. But that was the perspective I was writing it from, of somebody who had moved across the country and rejected their hometown.']]), ('Did you mean it when you said I was pretty?', [['It goes back to “I’m just a lady.” I think a lot of people feel this way, but I feel this way about myself where I have these moments where I feel very feminine. I feel like a lady. Then I have these moments that are polar opposites, where I definitely feel more masculine and I wanted to play around with that. Its just a simple sentiment. When someone says something like, “You’re beautiful,” I find myself having those moments where like, “Oh my God they said that to me. She said I was pretty.”

It’s so simple, and I wrote this song with my really good friend Nick Long. I remember we wrote that line and we were like, “It’s so simple. Is it too simple?” I don’t think its too simple. I think there’s a lot to be explored in that it means something different for everybody. Everyone wants to feel pretty. I want to feel pretty. You want to feel pretty.']]), ('I will keep on waiting for your love
 For you, I’ll wait
 I will keep on waiting for your', [['It’s so funny it was just a moment in time but it feels like forever. It was just a moment in time but I feel like that’s when the best songs come out. You feel something so intensely for week and then you’re like “Wow that was wild. Remember when I was a crazy bitch like four days ago? What the fuck was going on? Why was I screaming?” I definitely wrote this song at a point of having a full moment. It wasn’t forever. I don’t think anythings forever.']]), ('So I’ll wait for you, I’ll pray', [['I love to play with religious imagery, because its traditionally being gay and being religious have been oil and water. It’s not at all true. I’m not personally religious, but I do find religious imagery really beautiful. If I could work, I’ve always had this idea that I could work it into maybe being a point of acceptance. If I could use that religious imagery to talk about gay love because, there’s nothing different between gay people and straight people. I think that the issue is when these outside elements like religion and where you’re from come in to play. It is a conscious choice to use religious imagery. But I think specifically in this song, doesn’t it sound good? I go from Gods to praying, I was like “YES! FUCK YEAH!”']]), ('So tell me why my Gods look like you
 And tell me why it’s wrong', [['Yeah, the whole songs about being in love with this idea of a person and being in love with a figure and turning the person that you love into more of a shrine than an actual relationship. I think in that specific line, “tell me why my Gods look like you,” it’s like if you hold the person that you’re fucking, loving, dating, whatever, on that highest shelf, your adoration for them becomes greater than the actual relationship. I think that’s what that line’s about, just about really looking up to the person that you want romantically.']]), ('I love it when we play 1950', [['I think it’s an analogy. It’s a metaphor in the sense that I think I was using the idea of the way that queer people had to hide their love in history, throughout our history. Being a parallel to unrequited love. Feeling like somebody’s being cold to you in a public space. Somebody’s giving you the cold shoulder to bring you in more, and how that looks very similar to the way people once couldn’t be gay in public. I wanted to pay tribute to that point in history, in an empowering way. Now when we can be gay in public for the most part in the cities that I’ve lived. I wanted to pay tribute to that.']]), ('‘Cause I’m just a lady', [['Isn’t that funny? Because I’m not a lady. It was supposed to be a joke, that line, because I fall somewhere in between everything, and I love that. To say, “I’m just a lady” once was an insult. It’s reclaiming it.']]), ('I hate it when dudes try to chase me
 But I love it when you try to save me', [['I moved to LA, and I immediately went to school. I was in this environment where I was around all these kids who were also doing music. I knew I was gay. I knew what I wanted, but you have to remind yourself. It’s like whenever you change your settings, your location. I feel like I in particular started to think more about my identity and how it sits in a room, and who’s observing it.

I just had this moment where I was like, “I fucking hate it when dudes try to fuck me, but I also absolutely adore when ladies try to chase me.” That sentiment is pretty sick. I love that. I feel like a lot of women feel that way about attention. It’s like I hate it when I don’t want it, but you love intentional people coming for you and trying to catch you.']])]

annotations:
[('Ain’t Bobby so cool', [['Though Darius Rucker included this line in the original version of this song, Post is actually a huge Bob Dylan fan!

He covered his song, Don’t Think Twice, It’s All Right way back in 2013:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d_NS9Vd1sMA']]), ('I’m tangled up in blue', [['This is the title of another Dylan song, “Tangled Up in Blue”, off the same album, Blood on the Tracks']]), ('Put on a little Dylan sittin’ on a fence', [['A number of remaining lines pay homage to Bob Dylan, and this is the first example.

In Dylan’s “You’re a Big Girl Now”, he sang:

Bird on the horizon, sittin’ on a fence

All the Dylan lines referenced are from his album Blood on the Tracks.']]), ('Said I shot a man named Gray, took his wife to Italy
 She inherited a million bucks and when she died, it came to me', [['Before Genius, people used to have to ask each other about the meaning of great lines!

In his 1975 song “Idiot Wind”, Bob Dylan sang:

They say I shot a man named Gray and took his wife to Italy
She inherited a million bucks and when she died it came to me
I can’t help it if I’m lucky

Dylan’s management wasn’t exactly appreciative of the homage, and Hootie & the Blowfish were later sued for copyright infringement due to these lyrics.']]), ('[Bridge]', [['The beginning of Posty’s guitar solo here interpolates the guitar solo from “Champagne Supernova” by Oasis, sticking with the covering-90s-hit-songs theme.

Darius Rucker is also known for performing Champagne Supernova live at concerts:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ini09SE5W3o']]), ('I’m such a baby ’cause the Cowboys make me cry', [['Darius Rucker references the Miami Dolphins on the original version of the track due to the team’s lack of post-season success since Rucker was a child.

I’m such a baby ‘cause the Dolphins make me cry

On Post’s version of this song, he substitutes the Dolphins for the Dallas Cowboys, his favorite NFL team. The Cowboys, who are known as “America’s Team,” have also had postseason trouble in recent history, with their last Super Bowl win coming in January 1996.

Post has been a Cowboys fan for nearly his entire life. He references Dak Prescot, the quarterback of the Cowboys, on his December 2018 song, “Wow.,” and placed a $20,000 wager on a Cowboys game against fellow rapper YG in January 2019.']])]

In his Netflix documentary In Wonder, Shawn addresses how his life-long friend Brian’s accompanying him keeps him down “in the real world” and connects him with “friends from home”. He hopes he doesn’t let stardom break these bonds he values so much.']]), ('I wonder, when I cry into my hands

annotations:
[('Tastes like strawberries on a summer evenin’
 And it sounds just like a song
 I want more berries and that summer feelin’
 It’s so wonderful and warm', [['The comparison of the excitement about a new lover to all these different characteristics of the summer resembles to “Olivia”, a song Harry co-wrote for One Direction’s “Made in the A.M.”, which has the following lines:

The summertime and butterflies
All belong to your creation']]), ('Baby, you’re the end of June', [['As their relationship is still at the very beginning, he compares her to the end of June, and their relationship to the summer. June is a very calming and soothing month, as the sun is most likely shining all day long, and he feels like she did the same upon him. More than that, he already knows that the best days are ahead, July and August, and is really excited to dive into that with her.

This line is about the excitement felt while meeting a future loved one and building a relationship at an early level, like taking a glimpse into your own future and seeing bright smiles and warm hugs.

Additionally, Styles mentions strawberries in the previous line, and June-bearing strawberries are one of the most popular types of the fruit. They are usually ready to harvest in late June and are a favorite due to their large production of fruit.']]), ('Watermelon sugar high
 Watermelon sugar high
 Watermelon sugar high
 Watermelon sugar high
 Watermelon sugar', [['In response to Harry’s October tweet, fans were quick to research the phrase “watermelon sugar” and discovered a connection to Harry’s ex-girlfriend, model Camille Rowe—the two dated from July 2017 to July 2018. In Harry’s August 2019 Rolling Stone cover interview, featured writer Kid Harpoon commented on the break-up:

He went through this breakup that had a big impact on him […] He had a whole emotional journey about her, this whole relationship.

In the same interview, Harry also discussed the books he’d recently been reading, confessing:

Reading didn’t really used to be my thing. I had such a short attention span. But I was dating someone who gave me some books; I felt like I had to read them because she’d think I was a dummy if I didn’t read them.

When talking to Elle in February 2017, Camille revealed that one of her favourite books was “In Watermelon Sugar” by Richard Brautigan. The 1968 novel is set in a post-apocalyptic environment where individuals live in houses and wear clothing made of “watermelon sugar”, an element found by extracting the water out of watermelons, leaving the sugar behind.

In his March 2020 NPR Tiny Desk Concert Harry confirmed that the song’s title was inspired by “In Watermelon Sugar”:

We started some ideas and then I was with the guys that I made the first album with and we had this idea, this chorus melody, it was pretty repetitive. The Richard Brautigan book “In Watermelon Sugar” was on the table, and I was like ‘That’ll sound cool!’

In a November 2019 interview for Apple Music, Zane Lowe gave his own interpretation of the song:

Everyone’s kind of figured out what it is about, the joys of mutually appreciated oral pleasure. […] That’s what everyone’s saying…

In response, Harry neither confirmed nor denied Zane’s theory, preferring rather to leave it open to interpretation.']])]

As long as you love me
I’ll be your platinum
I’ll be your silver
I’ll be your gold

Featuring Big Sean, the track peaked at #6 on the Billboard Hot 100 and was certified quadruple-platinum in January 2017.']]), ('Forever’s not enough time to (Oh)
 Love you the way that I want (Love you the way that I want)', [['This line may reference Bieber’s hit “Forever” from his February 2020 album Changes. Featuring Post Malone and Clever, the song peaked at #24 on the Billboard Hot 100. In it, JB wishes for eternal marital bliss with his wife Hailey:

Could you be here with me forever, ever, ever?
Would you be here with me forever, ever, ever?

Two months before that song’s release, Biebs got the word inked on his neck. The same artist—Dr. Woo—gave his wife a similar neck tattoo with the word “lover” shortly before their September 2019 wedding.']]), ('Lookin’ back on my life, you’re the only good I’ve ever done (Ever done)', [["Bieber may be demonstrating some humility here, given his history of charitable actions. Most notably, he has worked extensively with the Make-a-Wish Foundation, which grants wishes to critically ill children. In August 2013, he broke the foundation’s record for most wishes granted by a musical artist. Other beneficiaries of Bieber’s time and/or money include the ACLU, PETA, and amfAR, an AIDS research charity to which Biebs donated $545,000 on a whim.

In February 2020, before the COVID-19 pandemic became an international crisis, Biebs donated $29,000 to Beijing Chunmiao Children Aid Foundation, sending a message of support on Instagram that foreshadowed the virus' worldwide impact:

Watching the news I couldn’t imagine how scary it would be if a new disease was effecting [sic] my wife and my family and friends. China we stand with you as a collective humanity and have made a donation to support.

Bieber went on to release two charity singles to help curb the outbreak. In May 2020, he collaborated with Ariana Grande for “Stuck With U,” the proceeds of which benefitted the First Responders Children’s Foundation. In December 2020, he teamed up with a London choir comprised of nurses, doctors, and other health care workers to record a version of his September 2020 hit “Holy.” The proceeds benefitted the UK’s National Health Service. Given all these acts of kindness, perhaps marrying Hailey wasn’t the only good he’s ever done."]])]

annotations:
[('You can turn me on with just a touch, baby', [['Abel expresses his great sensitivity towards the girl he’s with to show he’s really in love with her, or that he clings to every sign of affection, following what he says in the verse.

Also, even if that mustn’t be the same person he’s talking about in this track, Abel is not unfamiliar with this kind of touch. That could imply a reminiscence of feelings he had in his (fictional) past life, and the fact that he’s very sensitive towards women, and has always been.

This idea is somewhat confirmed in the chorus.']]), ('I’m running out of time
 ’Cause I can see the sun light up the sky', [['This line has several meanings:

First, he alludes to Las Vegas again. As mentioned in the pre-chorus of the song, Abel has a special emotional connection to the city. He recalls it here and automatically combines it with the chorus:

No, I can’t sleep until I feel your touch

Furthermore, Vegas is a city, known for being “alive” at night. Another reason this song’s story, or the whole album takes place in Vegas are Abel’s
repeated references of it, adding to the fact, that he feels at home there.

Abel fears, that he won’t be able to sleep, because he lost his loved one and needs to get her back to finally get sleep. At the end of his journey, he recalls this line. On “Final Lullaby”, the last track off the deluxe version of his album After Hours, Abel tries to accept the fact that he won’t find his love back in that night.

I’m running out of time
And you’ll always be on my mind

Another explanation could be his habit to be awake late at night, as already mentioned in “Alone Again”:

I’m falling only for the night

A possible reason for him being stressed during the day is his fame and popularity. During the day, Abel is blinded by the lights of police cars, but also by flashing camera lights, representing fame. Therefore, he likes to escape into the night, just like in his record “Snowchild”:

Leaving, leaving into the night
Now a nigga leaving, leaving
Leaving into the night, oh']]), ('I’m going through withdrawals', [['A “withdrawal” can both mean the behavior in which one prefers to be alone or also the physical and mental effects experienced when a person stops using a drug. Considering Abel’s historic of drug abuse, which is largely mentioned in his songs, the second one is more likely.

Moreover, in a 2016 interview with The Guardian he referred to the subject:

When I had nothing to do but make music, it was very heavy. Drugs were a crutch for me.']]), ('So I hit the road in overdrive, baby, oh', [["Here, Abel alludes to his habit of driving over the speed limit, which he has mentioned in several songs in the past, such as on “Heartless,”“ featured on his fourth studio album, After Hours:

I’ve been dodgin' death in the six-speed

Abel also admits his love for dangerous speeding on his September 2016 single “Starboy”

100 on the dash get me close to God

“Blinding Lights” was also originally teased in a German Mercedes-Benz commercial, where The Weeknd is shown driving an electric car while the song plays in the background.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C83VEu-yuYA"]]), ('I’ve been tryna call', [['The first line of this song represents Abel’s vulnerability. A theme explored throughout the rest of this song. On the song “Coming Down,” Abel expresses very similar feelings:

Pick up your phone
The party’s finished and I want you to know
I’m all alone

Without drugs, Abel feels a sense of loneliness. This is perhaps Abel’s truest and most authentic self.']]), ('I said, ooh, I’m blinded by the lights
 No, I can’t sleep until I feel your touch
 I said, ooh, I’m drowning in the night
 Oh, when I’m like this, you’re the one I trust
 Hey, hey, hey', [['This song directly follows the outro of “Faith,” where The Weeknd speaks about being in the back of a police car presumably after an overdose:

I ended up in the back of a flashing car
With the city shining on my face
The lights are blinding me again

The “lights” here not only represent the lights from the police car or the city but also the fame Abel’s enjoyed for his recording career. From stage lights to paparazzi camera flashes, he’s been “blinded” by many examples of a wealthy and successful life, and he doesn’t plan on stopping anytime soon. However, his celebrity life often overshadows his deep personal life. On his 2018 song “Privilege,” Abel discusses how many fans and media sources didn’t believe that he could have a real and genuine relationship with a partner because of his status in fame:

They said our love is just a game, I don’t care what they say

Nevertheless, his relationship seems to be real and sound, as he claims that it is the only thing that can keep him peacefully inserted in this lifestyle.

Abel also uses a similar line on “Snowchild,” the fifth track from After Hours:

Leaving, leaving into the night
Now a nigga leaving, leaving
Leaving into the night, oh']]), ('I’ve been on my own for long enough', [['Abel’s been on his own since around the age of 17 when he dropped out of high school and left home to never come back. This is referenced on many of his songs, like “Rolling Stone,” from his mixtape Thursday, where he said:

‘Cause I’ve been on these streets way too long, too long, too long
Baby, I’ve been on this too long

He’s also implying that he has been single for quite some time now and has forgotten how to love. From 2015 to 2019 Abel and model Bella Hadid had an on and off relationship, and after spending a few months apart, Abel seems to have lost his ability to love.

To add on, throughout After Hours, Abel plays with the idea of being “alone together” or simply “alone” on songs like “Save Your Tears”, “Faith,” and the opening track “Alone Again:”

‘Cause I don’t know if I can be alone again
I don’t know if I can be alone again']]), ('I look around and
 Sin City’s cold and empty (Oh)
 No one’s around to judge me (Oh)
 I can’t see clearly when you’re gone', [['Las Vegas is nicknamed “Sin City” due to the city’s overwhelming presence of crime, drugs, and sexual promiscuity—all important themes throughout The Weeknd’s career. He also explores hedonism on his August 2011 song “Heaven or Las Vegas.”

Abel experienced emptiness and heartbreak when he was briefly separated from Bella Hadid in 2019. The two have since reunited and emotionally completed The Weeknd.

Abel previously touched upon his need for Bella on his November 2019 single, “Heartless”:

You just came back in my life
You never gave up on me (Why don’t you?)
I’ll never know what you see (Why won’t you?)
I don’t do well when alone (Oh yeah)']]), ('I’m just calling back to let you know (Back to let you know)
 I could never say it on the phone (Say it on the phone)
 Will never let you go this time (Ooh)', [['This line is very similar to the song “Heartless,” released just days before this song. Here, Abel describes how his love for whom is presumed to be Bella Hadid is much stronger than he can say on the phone to her. This is different than the feelings Abel has shown in previous albums, with his typical themes usually revolving around never showing love towards anyone he is with and only using them for sex.']])]

lyrics:

annotations:
[('We should be heart to heart, my mind is on you
 I try, I really do', [['I think there’s two ways to take this lyric. I think you could take it in the most literal sense possible, like I need you on my chest, chest to chest, even though I guess hearts are on the opposite sides.  On the flip side, I think the way I see heart to heart is like, “Why can’t we just chop this up? Why can’t we just talk about this? Why can’t we just open our hearts to each other and figure out what went wrong?” You know what I’m saying?  ‘Cause a lot of relationships kind of end in a dismal spot. With my last one, there was kind of confusion, like distance kind of separated us, but there was never a true closure period or a true sign off message, like “Okay, this is why it happened.” Luckily, me and G are very stark in the contrast. I’m like completely over my last person type, so you can tell based off of talking to him that he’s still got the linger period. He’s still in that phase. Granted, his relationship was much deeper and more involved than mine. Mine was more of a summer fling type. A lot more innocent. At the end of the day, I personally don’t see myself doing that anymore. I’m just like a total free bird at this point, I feel like. But yeah, I think there’s still things that’ll bring up this person in my head. I try never to creep on their pages or anything. That definitely helps. I think when you’re constantly like, “Oh, do they have a new man? Do I need to like flex with a new girl or something?” Then like try to combat them, it’s like, no. You start playing these weird mental games. I just had to distance myself.']]), ('She’s sleeping on your side, what can I do?', [['It’s like you don’t even want this girl to be sleeping on this side. You’ll wake up and be like, “Man, I wish this was just my person. Straight up.” There’s not much you can do in that sense, but you think in the time being that this is gonna help. Whatever you’re doing. I think everybody notices in time that the only thing that can heal it is time. None of these coping mechanisms will actually end up helping you get out of this spot that you’re in mentally.']]), ('I’m looking at her face but I’m seeing you', [['Jack J: So I feel like this line is really kind of like, from certain girls that I’ve talked to, like a girl’s worst nightmare, almost. Like knowing that that they might be rebound or something, or knowing that they might be a void filler. I definitely, post my last relationship, I definitely kind of when into a phase where I was trying to fill the void by either going out or maybe I’ll just have a one night stand over here. It just means nothing at the end of the day. You think, personally, that it’s gonna help you cope, but it always ends up backfiring. ‘Cause, like I said, I’m looking at her face, but I’m seeing you. Even having that significant other around, having that touch, having that person around, that makes you instantly think of that person that you just lost, you know what I’m saying?']]), ('Even if I tell myself I can
 I know that I’ll break (I’ll break) before I can bend, yeah', [['Even in my head, if I’m like, “Nah, I’ll be good. I’m gonna go out with my friends, and we’re gonna have a good time. There’s gonna be some girl, and we’re gonna have fun. It’s gonna be great. Whatever.” Even if I tell myself I’m gonna get through this, I know that I’ll break before I can bend. Before I can adapt to the situation, the circumstances that I’m in, and really actually make it work for me, I know I’m gonna break. Because I’m gonna throw it on full fledge. I’m gonna drink as much as I can, I’m gonna go have as much fun as I can, and do all the stuff that I know I’ll regret. That’s pretty much the break. That’s me breaking.']]), ('Make it hard for me to love again
 Oh, where do I start and when do you end?', [["I feel like, in any relationship, you gotta do things that you don’t always wanna do to show someone you love ‘em. Or maybe that’s just my past experiences, and it’s not something that I should be doing. Maybe you should always feel comfortable. I definitely would do things that I normally wouldn’t do. I’m totally not the kind of guy to go get a bouquet of flowers and a teddy bear, but I specifically did that one time when my girlfriend was pissed at me. I showed up. I was like, “Hey, I’m so sorry. Let’s just go to dinner and talk about it.” She was thrilled. I was like, “Damn. That’s really all I gotta do? Okay.” But then after that, it’s like, “Wait, but you already got me the teddy and roses. I want this.” And that’s fine, too. Whatever. I feel like those are material things, and that’s probably why the relationship is over. 'Cause that’s not how a relationship should work. Maybe sometimes. I don’t know. Time is probably the most valuable thing you can give in any relationship, not even just a sexual relationship, in a friendship. You gotta give someone else time. You gotta give 'em an ear, so they can just talk about whatever. I feel like that’s very important, to listen to your other person."]]), ('No one compares to you', [['That’s just the way it is for me. I can’t find anyone who compares to my ex. There’s a lot of people that are amazing people, and I really respect them, but they’re not for me. They’re not for me to date. Maybe they’re just like my friend, or I’ll see ‘em every now and then, and it’s cool. We can do whatever when we see each other, but it’s not like a longterm thing. I think no one compares to her for me, because I can’t be with someone for as long as I was with her, if that makes sense. I can spend hours and hours, and days and days just really not even saying anything, but just feeling her presence. We would do that all the time. We’d just do everything together. That’s something that I have found that is really hard to do with someone else. For someone else, she might not be all that. It’s because of the experiences that I’ve had with her and shared with her, and now we have these memories, so it’s just tough.']]), ('There’s no way that someone else could make me ever
 Feel the same way that you do', [['It took me so long to get that in the studio, ‘cause I would sing, “There’s no way that someone else could make me ever feel the,” but it’s really, “There’s no way that someone else could ever.” Either way, I fucked it up massively so many times. It took me like an hour to get that line in the booth that day, I remember.']]), ('Every time I think I’ve found somebody
 I just wish that somebody was you', [['Someone that I love could really, really do almost anything to me, and my love for them won’t change. I’ve found that out in the past couple years. Some of the most unthinkable things. You never thought this person would do this, you never thought this person would do this, and then they do, and they do. I don’t know why that’s okay, but for some reason, love is just something that I have? I don’t know. Some people aren’t loving people, and that’s okay, but I’m a very emotional person. I like to share my feelings with people, and sometimes your boys aren’t the best people to share your feelings with. It’s nice to have that person, like a girl. For me, that’s how it is. It’s like, I don’t know. I’ll always love her. That’s just something that is like a given in my life, and I gotta go about my life knowing that.']]), ('Need you here but after all this time
 You can’t be replaced even if I try', [['When I find the one, I’m gonna try to hold onto her for as long as I can, but I wanna always make sure that I’m good to her and I’m good for her. Of course, I wanna fall in love and have this fantasy, family, and all that. It sounds amazing. I always wanna make sure I’m living a healthy life, and I always wanna make sure I’m being the best me that I can be. Sometimes, someone who seems like they’re everything to you and are perfect for you ends up maybe damaging certain other parts of your life. I know that it’s hard to see it when you’re in it, but an unhealthy relationship is actually very common, I feel like. Especially at the age of 20 and 22, or whatever. When I do find the one, I hope it’s in a couple years down the road, maybe five or six years down the road, ‘cause I have a lot of work to do personally to make sure I’m ready when I do find that person. I wanna be perfect, and not in a weird cheesy way. I just wanna be the best man possible, so I got work to do.']]), ('Thoughts of you and me keep passing by
 Like ships in the night, we never collide (Never collide)', [['I feel like this is a sick line to start the song off with, not only because of the amazing metaphor, because you never really hear about shipwrecks happening in the middle of the night. Maybe you do, I don’t know, but it’s very rare that two ships would collide. The ocean covers 75% of the world. I feel like, “thoughts of you and me keep passing by,” that’s a very real line for me. I think of my ex all the time. Maybe that’s weird, maybe it’s not, but for me that’s just how it is. Anytime I feel like I’m connecting with another girl, I start to question do I really fuck with this girl, or do I just kind of see my ex in her and miss that person? Having a person?']])]

name: Big Plans
lyrics:
[Verse 1: Daniel Seavey]
Work all day, work all night
Might not get no sleep tonight
Baby, can you stay up?
We could talk, we could dance
Don't matter the circumstance
We don't let it change us

[Pre-Chorus: Corbyn Besson]
That's the beautiful thing about us
'Fore all the diamonds and rings, we got trust
Roll with me, get it right, faded on a summer night
Let's see where it takes us

[Chorus: Zach Herron & All]
I got real big plans, baby, for you and me
So love me for who I am and for who I'm gonna be
Ain't got everything you want, but got everything you need
So take a chance, take a chance on me
I got real big plans, baby, for you and me
So love me for who I am and for who I'm gonna be
Ain't got everything you want, but got everything you need
So take a chance, take a chance on me

[Post-Chorus: Zach Herron & Jack Avery]
I got real big plans
Hold up, hold up, baby
I got real big plans
Hold up, hold up, baby
[Verse 2: Jonah Marais]
Know you're tired, know you're down
Know you wanna leave this town
Baby, give me one year, yeah
Take my hand, take a leap
Girl, you gotta wait and see
Where I take it from here

[Pre-Chorus: Corbyn Besson, All]
That's the beautiful thing about you
I know that you'd do the same in my shoes
Never switch, never stop, I could see us at the top
Girl, why don't we go there?

[Chorus: Zach Herron & All]
I got real big plans, baby, for you and me
So love me for who I am and for who I'm gonna be
Ain't got everything you want, but got everything you need
So take a chance, take a chance on me
I got real big plans, baby, for you and me
So love me for who I am and for who I'm gonna be
Ain't got everything you want, but got everything you need
So take a chance, take a chance on me

[Post-Chorus: Zach Herron & Jack Avery, Daniel Seavey]
I got real big plans
Hold up, hold up, baby (Oh)
I got real big plans
Hold up, hold up, baby
[Bridge: Jonah Marais, Jack Avery, Daniel Seavey, Corbyn Besson]
C'mon, c'mon, c'mon
Take a chance on
C'mon, c'mon, c'mon
Just take a chance on
C'mon, c'mon, c'mon
Take a chance on
Take a chance on me

[Chorus: Zach Herron & Jack Avery, Daniel Seavey]
I got real big plans, baby, for you and me
So love me for who I am and for who I'm gonna be
Ain't got everything you want, but got everything you need (Baby)
So take a chance, take a chance on me

[Post-Chorus: Zach Herron & Jack Avery, Corbyn Besson, Jonah Marais]
I got real big plans
Hold up, hold up, baby (Take a chance on me)
I got real big plans (Take a chance on me)
Hold up, hold up, baby

[Outro: Zach Herron]
I got real big plans
annotations:
[('Work all day, work all night
 Might not get no sleep tonight', [['Seavey is known to be consistently hard working and to often lose sleep working on new music, something which is backed up by many of his Instagram captions.

https://www.instagram.com/p/BpZZK93nkDw/

“Started writing a song and haven’t slept yet and then realized the sun was coming up and then realized I had a full day of interviews. Just how it be sometimes 🤔 gonna go do my hair now lol”']]), ('’Fore all the diamonds and rings, we got trust', [['During an interview with Genius for their track “Something Different,” Besson further expressed the importance of putting your relationship before the “flashiness” associated with portraying it online.

I think nowadays, especially with the media, relationships kinda lose the uniqueness and the connection because everything is so ‘flashy-flashy’ and you want to portray your relationship all over the internet, and you want people to think that your relationship is amazing, instead of you just thinking that your relationship is amazing.

https://genius.com/videos/Why-don-t-we-breaks-down-something-different']]), ('Never switch, never stop, I could see us at the top
 Girl, why don’t we go there?', [['In correspondence with the song’s theme of having ‘big plans’, these lines could have a double meaning.

Initially, it would seem that Besson is singing about his relationship with beauty and lifestyle vlogger, Christina Marie.
However, on closer inspection, he could be  suggesting that he see’s the band ‘at the top’ or believes that they belong there – with all five members singing the final line of the pre-chorus to reinforce that they are a collective.']]), ('Roll with me, get it right, faded on a summer night', [['To be “faded” typically means to be drunk or high. In America, the legal age to purchase alcohol or marijuana is 21, though an 18-year-old is able to purchase marijuana with a doctor’s recommendation.

The song was written before any group members were 21, but they may have been able to freely purchase either product in several countries they visited during the Invitation tour, including Spain and the Netherlands.

https://www.instagram.com/p/BjQlDJaHoLq/']])]

[('I wake up
 And I’m not so mad at Twitter now', [['The news can upset people. With people who use social media for their news, they often shift the blame to said social media platform. Twitter has a reputation for being a more heavily used social media platform for news. It is also one Jack goes back and forth on using, presumably for similar reasons. With 2020 being full of negative news-worthy events, Jack may have gotten either annoyed or depressed from waking up to these headlines. However, once promotion for the One Spectacular Night livestream concert and OK ORCHESTRA began, Jack made his return to Twitter.

https://twitter.com/JackAJRbrothers/status/1339990303290384388

The band also makes a reference to the famous social media platform in “Burn the House Down.”

…[S]hould I march with every stranger from Twitter to get shit done?

With Twitter’s heavy influence on the public, it has become a large platform for both promoting and suppressing political opinions. This has led to Twitter heavily moderating political tweets, more so than is normal. This may have come as a relief to Jack as most of Donald Trump’s tweets were flagged for similar reasons, and eventually led to a permanent ban on the former President’s account. With the band openly supporting Trump’s opposing candidate and the next President, Joe Biden, Jack’s use of Twitter may be starting to become more enjoyable than it has before.']]), ('[Outro]', [['As was previously done with “Bummerland,” “Way Less Sad” features a sort of morphing between instrumentation and vocals, a technique Ryan has been working on for years, namely during the quarantine months of COVID-19 while live shows were cancelled. During the One Spectacular Night livestream concert on December 26, 2020, the band hinted that there would be more of this style of production throughout OK ORCHESTRA.

The brotherly trio later accepted the fan-made-up word “instrumorphing” as the official term for this method of production on April 3, 2021.

https://twitter.com/AJRBrothers/status/1378349578622279684']]), ('Well, I can’t fall asleep, and I’m losing my mind
 ’Cause it’s half-past three and my brain’s on fire
 I been counting sheep, but the sheep all died
 And I’m trying too hard, but I can’t not try
 Well, I can’t fall asleep, and I’m losing my mind
 ’Cause it’s half-past three and my brain’s on fire
 I been counting sheep, but the sheep all died
 And I’m not dead yet, so I guess I’ll be alright', [['The second snippet of “Way Less Sad” was tweeted on Valentine’s Day, 2020, just three days before the single was released.

https://twitter.com/AJRBrothers/status/1361042854496378882

It features a play on the idiom “counting sheep,” which is where a person who is struggling to fall asleep thinks about counting sheep, hoping the monotonous action will cause them to eventually fall asleep.

As the band teased in a retweet, OK ORCHESTRA talks about several controversial topics, and “Way Less Sad” lives up to that claim with its topics of mental health, insomnia and overall lack of joy in life. There is also a direct reference to “Three-Thirty,” which talks about covering as many important topics in a promotional single as possible, insinuating that these important topics keep the brotherly trio up at night.



The clock that features the time of three-thirty is used as a prop in the music video as well as the backgrounds of both respective single artwork covers (1, 2) for “Bang!”']]), ('I’m a-okay, I’m a-okay', [['These lyrics were originally posted as a social media caption in the months leading up to the release of OK ORCHESTRA.

https://twitter.com/AJRBrothers/status/1354881972229857282

With the post being made on January 28, 2021, the caption was later confirmed to be lyrics due to a snippet being released a week and a half later on February 7, which showed Jack filming a scene for the music video.

https://twitter.com/AJRBrothers/status/1358505865968578560

As the song deals with the topic of mental health, Jack is telling himself and/or other people that he is okay despite knowing he is, in fact, not okay. While he is working toward an eventual state of joy in life, he is trying to tell himself to enjoy the current times of happiness while they last until he can achieve a better, more joyful state of mind in the future.']])]

annotations:
[('I want to know when I can go
 Back and get drunk with my friends
 I want to know when I can go
 Back and be young again', [['Chris Martin stated in an interview with Radio.com:

We’d been thinking so much about all these kids in refugee camps who are just like us. Well, I’m not a kid anymore but, people being labeled as just migrants or just refugees or just immigrants, and really they’re human people just like everyone else, and we were thinking about particularly the young people who’ve been displaced, who just want to go home and be normal just like everybody else.']]), ('Tulips the colour of honey today', [['Tulips have long played a significant role in Middle Eastern culture, with the plant having originated from Persia – Iran’s state emblem resembles a tulip. The plant is also used prominently in Persian poetry, from the 13th century works of Saadi to the 20th and 21st century works of Simin Behbahani. Persian poetry previously served as inspiration for Coldplay’s seventh album, A Head Full of Dreams.

While the significance of the tulips in this song is unclear, it is possible that the singer is simply describing the colours of the last batch of tulips that Rosaleem’s father sowed prior to their deaths – orange and yellow like honey.']]), ('Yes, she had eyes like the moon
 Would have been on the silver screen
 But for the missile monsoon', [['Rosaleem is described as having inherent beauty, so much so that it would have been possible for her to have lived to become a successful actress – the “silver screen” refers to the static screen at a cinema, where films are projected onto. Unfortunately this is not to be, as a monsoon of artillery is fired upon her residence without prejudice, killing her and her father.

By the end of December 2013, it had been estimated by the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (SOHR) that around 46,226 civilians had been killed by combatants in the Syrian Civil War. The Syrian Network for Human Rights (SNHR) has since estimated the number to have risen to 224,948 by the end of September 2019. Thousands of innocent, talented people in Syria, like Rosaleem, simply never got the chance to live out their lives and make their contributions to the world, as a result of the ongoing fighting in the country.']]), ('Boom boom kah, buba de kah
 Boom boom kah, buba de kah
 Boom boom kah, buba de kah', [['This onomatopoeic percussion, which accompanies the drum kit percussion, mimics the sound of conventional bombs exploding – translating it into a rhythm. Explosive attacks in Damascus, Syria, where this song is set, were frequent throughout the early stages of the Syrian Civil War, and has so far caused nearly 10,000 casualties in the city.

The onomatopoeia was created by Chris Martin’s youngest son, Moses Martin, and is performed by him on the track. While it is most prominent in the song’s bookends, it can still be heard throughout the track’s verses and choruses. Moses is also credited as a co-writer on this song.']]), ('Cherubim, Seraphim soon
 Come sailing us home by the light of the moon', [['Cherub and Seraphim are a pair of arch-angels. It is believed that they meet people once they die to either assure or warn them.

It showcases the pair sailing as refugees to find aid and escape the torments of the Syrian civil war.']]), ('Rosaleem of the Damascene', [['Martin directly references the 2018 bombings of Damascus, the capital of Syria. It showcases how the attack orchestrated by the US, UK, and France caused several casualties and displaced several people. It shows a girl named Rosaleem and her Baba (Persian for father) who are now refugees; they are labeled as Damascene which refers to someone who is an inhabitant of the city of Damascus.



(Aftermath of the Damascus bombing, April 14, 2018)

The lines also comment on the inherent beauty of the city of Damascus and the Arabian culture, and how everything got lost after the war.']])]

annotations:
[('Would’ve fought the whole town, so yeah', [['Small towns are a common theme in this album. In “Death By A Thousand Cuts,” Swift says the only thing she and her ex share is a small town. This imagery is powerful because it’s intimate: two lovers share a community and a life.']]), ('Lived in the shade you were throwing
 ’Til all of my sunshine was gone, gone, gone', [['Taylor uses a clever play on the word “shade”. “Throwing shade” is a slang term used to describe someone making negative comments about a person – generally in a sneaky, backhanded manner. This is not the first time she used the phrase to call out her haters – in “This Is Why We Can’t Have Nice Things” she sings:

But I’m not the only friend you’ve lost lately
If only you weren’t so shady

Taylor plays on the literal interpretation of the word which is: “comparative darkness and coolness caused by shelter from direct sunlight”. As shade takes away sunlight, this line details how the negativity of the song’s subject(s) took away from her happiness and light in her life.

This concept of light and dark is a continuous theme throughout the album. reputation was characterized by darker themes – visually, sonically and lyrically. Lover contrasts this with themes of color, brightness and light.

Thematically this represents a shift in Taylor’s life from darkness (negativity) to sunshine/light (positivity). This was visually portrayed in the album’s debut music, “ME!”:']]), ('How many days did I spend thinking
 ’Bout how you did me wrong, wrong, wrong?', [['The subject of this song is never explicitly mentioned. Although this song may be addressing negativity, hate and drama Swift may have faced in a more general sense, there is nonetheless speculation about the subject of the song.

An obvious pick is rap artist, Kanye West, whom Taylor had a highly publicized on-again-off-again feud with since 2009, when he infamously interrupted her VMA Best Female Video acceptance speech. Much of her reputation album revolved around this feud. Her track “This Is Why We Can’t Have Nice Things”, for example, shows how she felt done wrong as she sings:

It was so nice being friends again
There I was, giving you a second chance
But you stabbed me in the back while shaking my hand

Many fans, however, speculate that the song may be about ex-boyfriend Calvin Harris. He famously lashed out at Taylor on Twitter after their break-up. It’s interesting as there are no songs in Taylor’s discography known to be written about Calvin specifically, whereas Swift has penned tracks for most of her exes more explicitly. If the speculation is true, the song hits even harder as the only track penned about him is a track disregarding his importance in her life completely.']]), ('I forgot that you existed
 And I thought that it would kill me, but it didn’t
 And it was so nice
 So peaceful and quiet
 I forgot that you existed
 It isn’t love, it isn’t hate, it’s just indifference
 I forgot that you', [['Swift released her previous album, 2017’s reputation, after a spike in highly-publicized controversies. One example was a fallout with ex-boyfriend Calvin Harris, after word got out that she secretly co-wrote his hit “This Is What You Came For.” Some fans believe the reputation track “I Did Something Bad” took inspiration from this incident.

Perhaps the most vicious feud Swift has been involved in was her long-standing conflict with Kanye West, which was reignited when West put derogatory, sexist lyrics about her on his track “Famous” and claimed that Swift gave permission for him to say such things about her. She later explained her side of the story in a 2019 Rolling Stone interview, and touched upon a desire for vengeance on 2017’s “Look What You Made Me Do”:

The world moves on, another day, another drama, drama
But not for me, not for me, all I think about is karma

This chorus sees Swift saying goodbye to the toll these situations took on her, which she detailed throughout reputation. The delivery of the song matches the lyrics, with the phrases in the chorus being spoken flatly rather than sung — this further emphasizes the true indifference and lack of worry Swift feels towards the song’s subjects.']]), ('Laughed on the school yard
 As soon as I tripped up and hit the ground, ground, ground', [['This line uses the school playground as a metaphor for being in the limelight, where people laugh at one’s mistakes. It is one of the multiple references to school on the album — she uses a similar metaphor on “Miss Americana and The Heartbreak Prince”:

They whisper in the hallway, ‘She’s a bad, bad girl’ The whole school is rolling fake dice

And on the penultimate track, “It’s Nice to Have a Friend”:

School bell rings, walk me home']]), ('But then something happened one magical night', [['This sentiment is particularly shady when one considers Swift’s history of using magical, fairytale-esque imagery to talk about the highlights of her relationships, with key examples being her 2010 track “Enchanted” and even Lover’s title track.

Swift told Rolling Stone about the circumstances that allowed her to drop her past qualms in such a way:

It was sometime on the [2018] Reputation tour, which was the most transformative emotional experience of my career. That tour put me in the healthiest, most balanced place I’ve ever been. After that tour, bad stuff can happen to me, but it doesn’t level me anymore. […] Something about that tour made me disengage from some part of public perception I used to hang my entire identity on, which I now know is incredibly unhealthy.']]), ('Got out some popcorn
 As soon as my rep started going down, down, down', [['Swift thoroughly discussed the downfall of her public persona on her 2017 album reputation, on songs like “Delicate” and “Look What You Made Me Do.” To someone who didn’t listen to the full album, or want to hear Swift’s side of the story, the record’s singles made it look like the project focuses on her image, but Swift explained the symbolic meaning in a 2019 interview with Rolling Stone:

The one-two punch, bait-and-switch of Reputation is that it was actually a love story. It was a love story in amongst chaos. All the weaponized sort of metallic battle anthems were what was going on outside. That was the battle raging on that I could see from the windows.

Popcorn is recognized as the default movie theater snack, and people often say something like “get out the popcorn” when they’re excited to watch drama unfold.']]), ('In my feelings more than Drake, so yeah', [['If someone is “in [their] feelings,” they’re emotional, often after being hurt by someone else. Drake brought this term to modern-day prominence with his June 2018 track “In My Feelings,” on which he questioned whether his feelings for several love interests were reciprocated.

If the song is truly about Kanye West, this lyric could reference Drake’s own feud with the rapper. Swift mentioned their conflict in an August 2019 Rolling Stone interview:

[Kanye] gravely affected the trajectory of Drake’s family and their lives. It’s the same thing [he did to me]. Getting close to you, earning your trust, detonating you.

Swift attended Drake’s 30th birthday party in October 2016, and rumors popped up the next month about a potential collaboration, although it never happened. Swift teased this lyric with a badge featuring Drake in a photoshoot for Entertainment Weekly in May 2019:']])]

In fact, this line echoes an idea from LANY’s December 2015 song, “Walk Away”:

I’m too good at leaving love

On the other hand, Dua Lipa and Carew first dated from 2013 until 2017. They got back together in early 2018 but broke up for the second time in 2019.']]), ('Aren’t you the guy who tried to
 Hurt me with the word ”goodbye”?
 Though it took some time to survive you', [['This is a nod to Gloria Gaynor’s October 1978 hit song “I Will Survive”:

Weren’t you the one who tried to hurt me with goodbye?

Dua Lipa dated LANY’s frontman Paul Klein for five months in 2017 and 2018. Following the break-up, the band released their October 2018 album Malibu Nights, that was rumored to be heavily inspired by the split. On the album, Klein noticeably uses the word “goodbye” multiple times to characterize the ended relationship.

On “Thru These Tears,” he explains in the bridge that he is finally letting go:

You said it was over
But when we got closer
You cried on my shoulder
Goodbye

On “If You See Her,” he uses the word “goodbye” as a metonymy for the break-up:

The night before goodbye, she said forever (Ahh)



Dua Lipa wears a cropped LANY merchandise t-shirt as she is pictured alongside Paul Klein']]), ('Did the heartbreak change me? Maybe
 But look at where I ended up
 I’m all good already
 So moved on, it’s scary
 I’m not where you left me at all, so', [['In a September 2019 Vogue interview, Dua Lipa revealed that songs from her upcoming second studio album will be more “mature.” This song is speculated to be about her ex-boyfriends Isaac Carew and Paul Klein.

Dua and Isaac began dating in 2015 and ended their relationship after 18 months. Dua moved on to date Paul Klein, who is a member of the indie-pop band LANY, before getting back together with Isaac in June 2018. After nearly a year, the pair decided to split again, ending their relationship in June 2019.

It is also worth noting that later on in the second verse of the song, Dua mentions “goodbye[s]” and “walk[ing] away,” which were recurring themes on LANY’s October 2018 album Malibu Nights, rumoured to be about their break-up.']])]

annotations:
[('Cup of milk, let’s rock and roll', [['This line is a reference to the 90s advertising campaign Got Milk? encouraging the consumption of milk by Goodby Silverstein & Partners agency.

The milk mustache Jungkook ends up with in the music video, and that frequenly appeared on the commercials and propaganda for the brand, restates the reference.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hTru-Cy7taM&ab_channel=%E6%9B%B9%E5%A3%AC%E6%B6%93']]), ('Bring a friend, join the crowd, whoever wanna come along
 Word up, talk the talk, just move like we off the wall', [['BTS has a reputation for being unconventional and “off the wall” in terms of their lyrics, production, delivery, and even marketing. The term was used by the American youth brand Vans for promotional slogans since the 1970s. BTS stays on-brand by referencing a brand that is a staple to youth culture across the globe while maintaining the retro theme of the song.



The music video for the song features many odes to the King of Pop, Michael Jackson, through its choreography. Therefore, “off the wall” could also be a reference to the super-star’s seminal eponymous album and its title track.

With “Dynamite” being released at a high point in their career, BTS is able to gather a huge crowd with their unconventional ways. They hope that this song will resonate with as many people as possible. During the press conference for the song, member Suga commented saying,

We want to give strength during these times of difficulty for everyone, so we hope that many people listen to the song and feel comforted.

Another retro slang term used in these lyrics is “word up,” firstly popularized in hip-hop by Cameo’s eponymous hit song in the 1980s.']]), ('Rolling on like a Rolling Stone', [['This lyric is alluding to the famous saying “A rolling stone gathers no moss,” in the modern meaning of “stay active to avoid stagnation.” The BTS members are encouraging their listeners to stay active and hopeful with this uplifting lyric. This lyric is also an allusion to Bob Dylan’s hit June 1965 track, “Like a Rolling Stone”.

Keeping in the theme of the song, “rolling stone” could also be an allusion to the iconic magazine, Rolling Stone, a monthly magazine that focuses on popular culture founded in the 1960s.

The lyric could also be alluding to the legendary English rock band The Rolling Stones, formed in London in 1962.']]), ('King Kong, kick the drum', [['King Kong is a film monster (Kaiju), resembling an enormous gorilla, that has appeared in various media since 1933.']]), ('Jump up to the top, LeBron', [["LeBron James is one of the greatest basketball players of all time, partly due to his vertical leap—LeBron has a vertical jump of 40 inches, whereas an average NBA player can jump 28 inches.

Interestingly, Suga is seen wearing a Tune Squad basketball jersey from the 1996 movie Space Jam in the music video—this loosely ties in with the LeBron reference, who is set to be the protagonist in the sequel, Space Jam: A New Legacy.



Suga donning a vintage Tune Squad jersey.




Furthermore, these lines can also be interpreted as a metaphor for BTS' success on the charts, as they’ve “jumped” from a rookie K-pop group to international superstars."]])]

name: Smile
lyrics:
[Chorus]
Yeah, I'm thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Gotta say it's really been a while
But now I got back that smile (Smile)
I'm so thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Now you see me shine from a mile
Finally got back that smile (Smile)

[Verse 1]
Every day, Groundhog Day
Goin' through motions felt so fake
Not myself, not my best
Felt like I failed the test

[Pre-Chorus]
But every tear has been a lesson
Rejection can be God's protection
Long hard road to get that redemption
But no shortcuts to a blessin'

[Chorus]
Yeah, I'm thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Gotta say it's really been a while
But now I got back that smile (Smile)
I'm so thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Now you see me shine from a mile
Finally got back that smile (Smile)
[Verse 2]
I'm 2.0, remodeled
Used to be dull, now I sparkle
Had a piece of humble pie
That ego check saved my life

[Pre-Chorus]
Now I got a smile like Lionel Richie
Big and bright, need shades just to see me
Tryna stay alive just like I'm the Bee Gees (Oh, woah)
A Mona Lisa masterpiece (Now I'm)

[Chorus]
Yeah, I'm thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Gotta say it's really been a while
But now I got back that smile (C'mon, smile, woo)
I'm so thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful (So grateful)
Now you see me shine from a mile
Finally got back that smile (Smile, oh, oh)

[Bridge]
I'm so thankful
'Cause I finally, 'cause I finally
I'm so grateful
'Cause I finally, 'cause I finally (Oh)
[Chorus]
Yeah, I'm thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Gotta say it's really been a while
But now I got back that smile (Woo, smile)
I'm so thankful
Scratch that, baby, I'm grateful
Now you see me shine from a mile
Finally got back that smile (Smile, oh, oh)

[Outro]
I'm so thankful
'Cause I finally, 'cause I finally
Smile (Oh)
I'm so grateful
'Cause I finally, 'cause I finally
Smile (Oh, oh)
annotations:
[('But now I got back that smile (Smile)', [['Katy has talked before about suffering from depression after her career had a signifcant downward slope.
Her friend and fellow artist, Sia, spoke on this subject:



“She had a real breakdown… She’s on stage with 10 candied lollipops and clowns and dancers, selling the dream, the joy, the happiness — and that’s really hard sometimes when you’re not feeling it yourself.”

In People magazine, Katy also spoke about her struggles in an interview.
Taken from the magazine : “The singer [Perry] burst onto the pop charts with her 2008 hit "I Kissed a Girl,” then shot to teenage superstardom with her 2010 album Teenage Dreams… but four years later she felt devastated when Witness, an album she called “purposeful pop”, “failed to make the same impact”.
https://s3.amazonaws.com/filepicker-images-rapgenius/al5XUdw2TOycdkXBuAbD_mgid%3Aao%3Aimage%3Amtv.com%3A650040
After being in the spotlight for so long, having a flop  affected Katy very badly, as Sia said.
“Working on her mental health was the best thing she ever did,” the singer said.']]), ('Not myself, not my best
 Felt like I failed the test', [['“Not my best” is a reference to her previous album and she “failed the test” as it received a lot of criticism from the test of the press and public']]), ('Every day, Groundhog Day', [['In reference to the film Groundhog Day (1993) starring Bill Murray where he finds himself stuck in a time loop, forcing him to live the same day many times. A day that is constantly repeated can symbolize a monotonous cycle that Katy Perry wants to break. This usually occurs when someone is unhappy, the monotony and sadness she escapes from allow her to be thankful now and happy (‘now I got back that smile’).']]), ('But every tear has been a lesson', [['Katy is talking about her last record “Witness” journey that brought her a series of hatred with all her image after approach about totalitarian governments, sexism, vulnerability and female empowerment, and that caused her worst phase of clinical depression, commented by her in her last interviews.

Katy had cut and platinum her hair, bringing a mature look that was not well regarded after all her career being consumed by her sexualization.



The eyes and tears were a great image at her last album, so she means that every song going in the wrong way of the charts and every judgment made her better.



At the Witness: The Tour’s end, she said on a instagram post revealing a new tattoo referencing the era: […] this journey has taught me many lessons with a few tears along the way BUT I am happy to report a sense of real resilience as we wrap.']]), ('Used to be dull, now I sparkle', [['Katy takes back what she sung in her 2017 track “Mind Maze,” suggesting that she has healed and moved on from her depression:

I used to be so sparkling
But now it’s not so charming']]), ('Had a piece of humble pie', [['This line likely refers to Katy’s previous album, Witness, being widely considered a huge step back for the artist. It was met with much criticism.']]), ('Big and bright, need shades just to see me', [['In celebration of the release of “Daisies,” Katy launched an digital flower-shop, offering several free virtual bouquets. One of the bouquets available on the shop is named “Big and Bright,” which Katy references in this line.']]), ('A Mona Lisa masterpiece (Now I’m)', [['Katy is comparing her smile to one of the most famous smiles in all of history–the titular subject of Leonardo Da Vinci’s Mona Lisa, who seems to change between a smiling and then neutral expression.



In 2000, a Harvard neuroscientist determined that this occurs because of “how the human visual system is designed, not because the expression is ambiguous.” The Atlantic also stated that “the magic of the Mona Lisa’s smile is that it seems to react to our gaze”.']]), ('Tryna stay alive just like I’m the Bee Gees (Oh, woah)', [["“Stayin' Alive” is one of the Bee Gees‘ nine No. 1 singles on Billboard’s Hot 100. The 70s disco track details the literal feeling of staying alive, even through its heartbeat production and breath-like lyrics:

Ah, ha, ha, ha, stayin' alive, stayin' alive
Ah, ha, ha, ha, stayin' alive"]]), ('Now I got a smile like Lionel Richie', [['One of the best-selling artists of all time, Lionel Richie had his heyday as a solo artist and lead singer for the Commodores in the 70s and 80s.

Perry and Richie were also co-judges on the reboot of television series American Idol.




American Idol judges: Richie, Perry, and Luke Bryan']])]
